semantic_equivalence_artifact.original_latex_theorem:
[Transitivity]\label{transitivity}
Let $\gamma:\Gamma$, $\delta:\Delta$ and $\omega:\Omega$ be contexts. If $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}\;\rangle$ is a canonical context homotopy equivalence between $\gamma$ and $\delta$ and $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}'\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}'\;\rangle$ is a canonical context homotopy equivalence between $\delta$ and $\omega$ then there is a canonical context homotopy equivalence $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}''\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}''\;\rangle$ between $\gamma$ and $\omega$ such that $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\gamma\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}''(\gamma)=\textnormal{\texttt{c}}'(\textnormal{\texttt{c}}(\gamma))$ and equivalently $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\delta\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}''(\delta)=\textnormal{\texttt{d}}(\textnormal{\texttt{d}}'(\delta))$.

\proof
By induction on the complexity of $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}\;\rangle$. If $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}\;\rangle$ is of the form \texttt{(a)} then $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}'\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}'\;\rangle$ is of the form \texttt{(a)} as well and we are done. Let $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}\;\rangle$ be of the form \texttt{(b)}, hence $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}'\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}'\;\rangle$ is of the form \texttt{(b)} as well. Then $\gamma  : \Gamma$, $\delta:\Delta$ and $\omega:\Omega$ are of the form $\gamma'  : \Gamma',x : A(\gamma')$ and $\delta' :  \Delta',\underline{x}: A'(\delta')$ and $\omega':\Omega',\underline{\underline{x}}:A''(\Omega')$ respectively. Moreover there are a canonical context homotopy equivalence: \begin{center}$\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\gamma':\Gamma'\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\textnormal{\texttt{f}}(\gamma'):\Delta'$\\ $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\delta':\Delta'\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\textnormal{\texttt{g}}(\delta'):\Gamma'$\end{center} and a canonical homotopy equivalence: \begin{center} $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\gamma':\Gamma',x:A(\gamma')\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;f(\gamma',x):A'(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}(\gamma'))$\\ $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\gamma':\Gamma',\underline{x}':A'(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}(\gamma'))\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;g(\gamma',\underline{x}'):A(\gamma')$\end{center} between $A(\gamma')$ and $A'(\delta')$ relative to $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{f}}\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{g}}\;\rangle$ in such a way that the extension: \begin{center} $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\gamma' : \Gamma',  x:A(\gamma')\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;(\textnormal{\texttt{f}},\textnormal{\texttt{f}}_{m+1})(\gamma',x):\Delta',A'$\\ $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\delta' : \Delta', \underline{x}:A'(\delta')\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;(\textnormal{\texttt{g}},\textnormal{\texttt{g}}_{n+1})(\delta',\underline{x}):\Gamma',A$\end{center} of $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{f}}\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{g}}\;\rangle$ via $\langle\;f\;|\;g\;\rangle$ (\autoref{context homotopy equivalence expansion}) is the given $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}\;\rangle$. Analogously, there are a canonical context homotopy equivalence: \begin{center}$\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\delta':\Delta'\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'(\delta'):\Omega'$\\ $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\omega':\Omega'\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\textnormal{\texttt{g}}(\omega'):\Delta'$\end{center} and a canonical homotopy equivalence: \begin{center} $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\delta':\Delta',\underline{x}:A'(\delta')\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;f'(\delta',\underline{x}):A''(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'(\delta'))$\\ $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\delta':\Delta',\underline{\underline{x}}:A''(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'(\delta'))\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;g'(\delta',\underline{\underline{x}}'):A'(\delta')$\end{center} between $A'(\delta')$ and $A''(\omega')$ relative to $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{g}}'\;\rangle$ in such a way that the extension: \begin{center} $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\delta':\Delta',\underline{x}:A'(\delta')\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}',\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'_{m+1})(\delta',\underline{x}):\Omega',A''$\\ $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\omega' : \Omega', \underline{\underline{x}}:A''(\omega')\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;(\textnormal{\texttt{g}}',\textnormal{\texttt{g}}'_{n+1})(\omega',\underline{\underline{x}}):\Delta',A'$\end{center} of $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{g}}'\;\rangle$ via $\langle\;f'\;|\;g'\;\rangle$ (\autoref{context homotopy equivalence expansion}) is the given $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{c}}'\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{d}}'\;\rangle$. By inductive hypothesis there is a canonical context homotopy equivalence $\langle\;\textnormal{\texttt{f}}''\;|\;\textnormal{\texttt{g}}''\;\rangle$ between $\gamma'$ and $\omega'$ such that: \begin{center} $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\gamma'\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\textnormal{\texttt{f}}''(\gamma')=\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}(\gamma'))$ and $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\omega'\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\textnormal{\texttt{g}}''(\omega')=\textnormal{\texttt{g}}(\textnormal{\texttt{g}}'(\omega'))$ \end{center} Let us consider the canonical homotopy equivalence: \begin{center} $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\gamma':\Gamma',x:A(\gamma')\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\tilde{f}(\gamma',x)\equiv f'(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}(\gamma'),f(\gamma',x)):A''(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}(\gamma')))$\\ $\boldsymbol{\lfloor}\gamma':\Gamma',\underline{\underline{x}}'':A''(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}(\gamma')))\boldsymbol{\rfloor}\;\tilde{g}(\gamma',\underline{\underline{x}}'')\equiv g(\gamma',g'(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}(\gamma'),\underline{\underline{x}}'')):A(\gamma')$\end{center} relative to $(\textnormal{\texttt{f}}'\textnormal{\texttt{f}};\textnormal{\texttt{g}}\textnormal{\texttt{g}}')$ and let us observe that: $$\begin{aligned}
